---
description: JSON data-access rules — how routes/services/repositories touch data
globs: apps/api/src/{data,services,routes}/**/*.ts
alwaysApply: false
---

# Data layer

- All reads/writes go through `apps/api/src/data/`. NEVER import `fs` or touch
  `/data/*.json` directly from a route or service.
- Use `readJson` / `updateJson` from `jsonStore.ts`. Writes are atomic (temp file + `rename`) —
  don't reimplement file writing.
- Mutations that must reject duplicates throw `ConflictError` from INSIDE the `updateJson`
  updater callback, so the check and write are atomic.
- IDs are prefixed, zero-padded strings (`book_001`). Generate a new id by incrementing the
  highest existing one (see `generateNextBookId` in `books.repository.ts`), never random/UUID.
- Repositories are entity-scoped (`books.repository.ts`); services orchestrate them
  (`books.service.ts`). Keep filtering/pagination/search in services, not repositories.

Example mutation:
```ts
await updateJson<Book[]>(dataFiles.books, (books) => {
  if (books.some((b) => b.isbn === payload.isbn)) {
    throw new ConflictError(`A book with ISBN ${payload.isbn} already exists`);
  }
  return [...books, newBook];
});
```
